    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-05-03T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-05-03T14:00:00-05:00" n="287"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d287">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">362.115/141b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="26" xml:id="d287fn26">The same, <hi rend="italic">mutatis
                            mutandis</hi>, on the same date to the Ambassador in the United Kingdom
                        (No. 189).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-05-03T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 3, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>250. Referring to the German Decree of April 26, 1938 requiring the declaration
                    of property of Jews including those of foreign nationality apparently for the
                    purpose of taking over such properties, we are anxious to be informed what
                    action if any is contemplated by the French Government.</p>
                <p>This Government regards the German contemplated action as violating its treaty
                    signed December 8, 1923.<note n="27" xml:id="d287fn27">Treaty of Friendship,
                        Commerce and Consular Rights Between the United States and Germany, <ref
                            target="frus1923v02#pg_29">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1923, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 29</ref>.</note> You may orally so
                    inform the Foreign Office and also state that a similar inquiry is being made of
                    Great Britain.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
